<title>Sprite</title>
<h1>
<!WA0><img align=bottom src="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/Research/Projects/sprite/spritelogo.gif" width=138 height=94 alt="">
The Sprite Operating System</h1>
<hr>
<h2>New address!</h2>
The new address for these pages is <!WA1><a
href="http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/projects/sprite">
http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/projects/sprite</a>
<p>
<hr>
Sprite is a research operating system developed at the University of
California, Berkeley, by John Ousterhout's research group.
<p>
Sprite is
a distributed operating system that provides a single system image to
a cluster of workstations.  It provides very high file system performance
through client and server caching.  It has process migration to take
advantage of idle machines.  It was used as a testbed for research in
log-structured file systems, striped file systems, crash recovery, and
RAID file systems, among other things.
<p>
The Sprite project has now ended, although Sprite is still running on a
few machines.  If you have a DECstation 5000/200 or a SparcStation 2, you
could try running Sprite off the Sprite CD-ROM.
<p>
John Ousterhout has a <!WA2><a href="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/Research/Projects/sprite/retrospective.html">retrospective</a>
on the Sprite project.
<hr>
<h2>Sprite papers</h2>
There are many <!WA3><a href="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/Research/Projects/sprite/sprite.papers.html">papers</a> on Sprite.
<h2>Ftp</h2>
Sprite files are available by <!WA4><a href="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/Research/Projects/sprite/sprite.ftp.html">ftp,</a>
including the source code.
<!WA5><a href="ftp://parcftp.xerox.com/pub/sprite">Brent Welch</a> has a
Sprite ftp site.
<h2>Sprite network traces (SOSP 91)</h2>
The Sprite group traced network file system operations for our SOSP '91 paper
<!WA6><a href="ftp://ftp.cs.berkeley.edu/ucb/sprite/papers/measureSOSP91.ps">
Measurements of a Distributed File System</a>.
<!WA7><a href="http://now.CS.Berkeley.EDU/Xfs/SpriteTraces/">Information</a>
on accessing the trace data and information on the traces.
<h2>Sprite CD-ROM</h2>
<!WA8><a href="http://www.cdrom.com/titles/sprite.html">Information</a> on
on purchasing the Sprite CD-ROM.
This CD-ROM contains Sprite source code, documentation, and a bootable
version of Sprite.  You can get a
<!WA9><a href="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/Research/Projects/sprite/cdrom.ls_lR.Z">listing</a> of the cdrom contents (long).
Brent Welch has
<!WA10><a href="ftp://parcftp.xerox.com/pub/sprite/bringup.notes">notes</a>
on booting Sprite from the CD-ROM and a
<!WA11><a href="ftp://parcftp.xerox.com/pub/sprite/bugs">bug list</a>.
